              <table id="EditorialReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Amazon.com:</DIV>
                <span id="Label1">Musicians and artists might need talent to succeed, but writers don't, says Jerry Cleaver in <I>Immediate Fiction</I>. Cleaver allows that talent is needed to win a National Book Award, say, but otherwise, any of us can do it. All we need is the ability to "develop and exercise sadistic license." The operative word is <i>conflict</i>. As Cleaver puts it, "Happy lives make lousy novels.... If the characters are having a good time, the reader is not." He takes the mystery out of fiction writing. You don't have to write about what you know, he says; write what you can imagine. Don't fret if you can't find large chunks of time to write. Start with five minutes on weekdays and 20 on weekends, and you'll have 100 to 300 pages by year's end. Perhaps most refreshing about Cleaver's approach is the lack of directives. Some writing instructors demand that you work with an outline; others forbid it. Cleaver claims that teachers who tell you to do it one way or the other are telling you not how you work best, but how they work best. <I>--Jane Steinberg</I></span>
              
</td></tr></table>
              <table id="CustomerReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Customer reviews:</DIV>
                
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">good coaching</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-18</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>In team sports, the job of a good coach is to clear away the extraneous and refocus their players on what is fundamentally important.  So a pitching coach may notice a player dropping his arm a little, or a batting coach may notice that a hitter has added something new to the trigger at the start of his swing (which has slowed him through the strike zone).  A hoops coach may notice that a guard has stopped squaring up before releasing the jump shots that are his bread and butter.  And so on.
<br />
<br />And this coach brings his player back to what's important, and to what's necessary, and to what works.  
<br />
<br />It's not that the extra stuff (the raw talent, the flair that each player possesses) is irrelevant.  It's that each player will bring what's uniquely personal with him anyway.  As long as the lack of fundamentals doesn't undermine him.
<br />
<br />And so we come to Jerry Cleaver, writing coach, and his patient approach to hammering home the fundamentals of story.  Jerry preaches WANT + OBSTACLE + ACTION + RESOLUTION + EMOTION + SHOWING because without these a writer may not get the chance to show what he or she can do.  Without these, it seems unlikely that your "stuff" will ever get you to the show.
<br />
<br />I was a reporter for some years, and a business writer for a long time after that, but I never got anywhere with my fiction.  Having absorbed the lessons in this book, I understand why.  
<br />
<br />I'm grateful whenever I'm on the receiving end of someone who deals straight.  Jerry Cleaver seems to have done that here.  And my work has improved significantly since I read him.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Writing Craft Made Understanable</div>
